two classes: those whose solubility decreases with increasing temperature display lower critical solution temperature (LCST) type behaviour, while those with upper critical solution temperature (UCST) type behaviour display the opposite trend [4,5]. LCST type polymers are far more common than UCST type in aqueous solutions [4,16,17]. Six primary categories of LCST-type thermoresponsive polymers were identified by Chen et al. [18] poly[oligo(ethylene glycol) (meth)acrylate]s [19–24], poly(2-alkyl-2-oxazo-line)s [23], poly (vinyl methyl ether)s [25,26], polypeptides [27,28], N-alkylsubstituted poly(aminoethyl methacrylate)s [29–32], and Nsubstituted poly(meth)acrylamides [33]. From this last category, poly(N-isopropylacrylamide) (PNIPAM) is by far the most studied neutral thermoresponsive polymer owing in part to its low sensitivity to environmental conditions (e.g. salt, pH, polymer concentration), its biologically relevant transition temperature (32 °C) and its structural similarity to proteins [34,35]. However, PNIPAM is cytotoxic under certain conditions [36], which has led to a number of alternative, biocompatible polymers receiving increasing interest [15,22,37]. Recent advances in monomer synthesis have facilitated a rapid expansion in the range of available monomers [4]. The LCST transition temperature may be tuned by varying the hydrophilicity of the monomer [18], or through copolymerisation of monomers with differing hydrophilicity [4,19]. For example, increasing the length of the hydrophilic ethylene glycol side chain length raises the LCST of oligo ethylene glycol methacrylates (OEGMAx), where x is the molar mass of the monomer [19]. Incorporation of additional components such as bioconjugates [38–41], ligands [42], fluorescent markers [43,44], or charged moieties [41,45–47] into copolymers can further modify the phase transition, add greater specificity for interactions between polymers and other solutes [39,45,46], or even facilitate new ways to study their behaviour [44]. Improved synthetic methods, such as reversible additionfragmentation chain transfer (RAFT) or atom transfer radical polymerisation (ATRP) [20–22,24], have allowed access to a wide range of polymer geometries and architectures such as statistical, block and gradient copolymers, stars, dendrimers and gels (Fig. 1) [5,37]. Differing regions of hydrophilicity allows many of these molecules to self-assemble, which is particularly promising for controlled release applications [12]. Decorating surfaces with initiator sites and subsequent polymerisation directly from the surface allows the formation of polymer brushes [48]. This is known
as the grafting from approach which allows higher grafting densities than the sterically hindered adsorption of end-functionalised chains to the surface, i.e. the grafting to approach. Polymer brushes are assemblies of polymer chains end-grafted at a sufficiently high areal density to force self-interaction. The forced confinement of the chains, in addition to the chemistry of the polymer, allows tailoring of interfacial properties such as wettability, adhesion and lubricity [10]. These properties can be switched in responsive polymer brushes as the polymer conformation swells and contracts with changing solvent quality. In addition to the potential applications noted previously, surface-confined thermoresponsive polymer brushes have been utilised in applications ranging from chromatography supports [49–51] to the enzyme free removal of cells from tissue culture substrates [52–54]. Many factors affect the properties of thermoresponsive polymers in solution, including the polymer concentration [55,56], molecular weight (MW) [56–58], end-group chemistry [57–60], the presence of cosolutes such as salts and osmolytes [6,8,61], and the composition of the solvent [6,8]. Understanding the effect of added salt is important for many applications of these polymers as the background electrolyte concentration in the human body is around 100 mM [7]. It has been demonstrated extensively that the temperature response of ungrafted chains is affected by both the concentration and identity of ions in solution [6,8,61]. The tendency to either raise or lower the LCST of the polymer is often correlated with the degree to which a particular ion is excluded or accumulated at the polymer-solvent interface. However, this simplistic picture is inadequate in many cases [62,63]. Recent studies on thermoresponsive polymer brushes have shown that the influence of added ions cannot be solely explained by a shift in the LCST [64–68]. Herein, we seek to demonstrate the importance of architecture on the specific ion response of thermoresponsive polymers. Firstly, a brief overview of how composition and architecture affects the thermoresponse in salt-free water, with a focus on polymer brush coated surfaces provides context to observed salt-dependent behaviour. This is followed by a discussion of the current experimental and theoretical understanding of specific ion effects on thermoresponsive polymers with ungrafted and gel architectures. Comparison of these results with studies on brushes then allows the emerging picture of how the confined architecture of polymer brushes influences specific ion effects to be emphasised. Discussion of multi-responsive polymers containing pH and salt sensitive ionisable groups has been avoided as there is a strong, often non-monotonic [69], interplay between the degree of charge, the ionic strength and the temperature response [29,30,32,47,70–74]. Furthermore, reports of polymer brushes synthesised using the grafting from approach have already been discussed comprehensively by Klok and co-workers [75,76]. Below we demonstrate the need for systematic studies to elucidate the complex interplay of solution and polymer composition convolved with polymer architecture in determining the overall response to temperature.
2. Thermoresponsive polymers
2.1. The lower critical solution temperature of ungrafted chains
This article focusses on neutral polymers that have an LCST in aqueous solutions. In these systems, the LCST arises from the competition between enthalpic gain from hydration of hydrophilic moieties against the entropic penalty for the hydration of hydrophobic moieties via an ice-like, clathrate cage [33]. At temperatures above the LCST intra- and inter-molecular bonds dominate and the polymer collapses leading to an increase of the system entropy via the release of bound water molecules. It must
Fig. 1. Different architectures of a typical thermoresponsive polymer, poly(Nvinylcaprolactam) (PNVCL). Reprinted from Ref. [37] with permission from Elsevier, copyright (2016).
430 T.J. Murdoch et al. / Journal of Colloid and Interface Science 526 (2018) 429–450


be noted that in most cases, critical solution temperatures (CSTs) at a single condition are reported, while the LCST corresponds to a minimum in a full phase diagram of CST as a function of polymer volume fraction, and occurs at what is defined as the critical concentration (/c) [35,77]. The term CST has been adopted throughout this article for all polymers exhibiting an LCST type transition. Three limiting behaviours for /c at infinite molar mass have been identified as outlined schematically in Fig. 2 [35,78]. Type I corresponds to classical Flory-Huggins mixing behaviour where /c approaches zero (e.g. poly(2-oxazoline) (POX) [79] or PNVCL [37]), Type II display a single non-zero value of /c (e.g. PNIPAM [35]) while Type III has one zero value of /c and two non-zero values (e.g.poly(vinyl methyl ether) (PVME) [80]). Type II behaviour is predicted by Flory-Huggins theory if an empirical concentration dependent Flory interaction parameter, veff ðT; /Þ is introduced [35,81]. Note that there is no consensus on the value of veff ðT; /Þ even for the well-studied PNIPAM, and therefore must be treated with care when used for predictive purposes [82]. Type III behaviour is associated with strong solvent interactions that lead to the formation of molecular complexes [80]. A range of techniques allows various aspects of the phase transition to be interrogated. Cloud point measurements provide a simple estimation of the CST where a sharp transition is observed in most cases [77]. PNIPAM shows significant kinetically induced hysteresis between heating and cooling associated with strong intermolecular hydrogen bonding (Fig. 3Aii), while the hysteresis for POEGMA copolymers with weaker intermolecular bonding is minimal (Fig. 3Ai) [34]. The degree of hysteresis is affected by the differing kinetics of hydrogen bond breaking and formation as revealed by dielectric relaxation spectroscopy [83,84]. Significant hysteresis is observed for PNIPAM for heating-cooling rates greater than 0.1 °C min1 [77,83]. Other spectroscopic techniques such as NMR [85], Raman [86,87] and FTIR [86–89] allow the hydration of individual moieties to be tracked as used by Wu and co-workers on POEGMA copolymers to highlight the tendency of polymers to rearrange to maximise contact between the solvent and hydrophilic moieties in the aggregated state [90]. Transition thermodynamics can be determined by differential scanning calorimetry (DSC) with the CST corresponding to an endothermic peak associated with breaking water-water hydrogen bonds in the clathrate cage [25,91]. Scattering techniques such as small angle neutron scattering (SANS) [92,93], small angle X-ray scattering (SAXS) [92] and dynamic light scattering (DLS) [93,94] provide additional knowledge of the change in size and conformation of the chains through the transition. Further insights are accessible through molecular dynamics (MD) simulations of oligomers [90,95].
2.2. Effect of polymer architecture on the temperature response
2.2.1. Block and statistical copolymers
Polymer architecture has a significant effect on both the locus of the thermal transition and the solution conformation of the polymer. For example, copolymers composed of blocks with different CST values undergo temperature dependent self-assembly due to the difference in hydrophilicity of each block [15,40,98–101]. In most cases statistical copolymerisation of monomers of varying hydrophilicity leads to a single intermediate, composition dependent, value of the CST [19,21,55,102]. However, distinct transitions can occur if the difference in CST of the monomers is large enough, leading to self-assembled structures similar to block copolymers [103,104]. Furthermore, block copolymers can have statistical copolymer-like behaviour with a single broadened transition observed if the CST of each block is similar [105]. The phase behaviour of copolymers may also be influenced by bonding interactions not present in the homopolymers. For example, intramolecular hydrogen bonding between poly(2-ethyl-2oxazoline) (PEtOx) and PNIPAM in PNIPAM-b-PEtOx-b-PNIPAM copolymers leads to a CST lower than that exhibited by either homopolymer [106].
2.2.2. Gels
Thermoresponsive gels are chemically or physically crosslinked polymer networks that undergo a volume phase transition (VPT) [107,108]. The VPT is heavily dependent on the limiting behaviour of the equivalent free polymer chains as they can be considered as high MW polymers with the maximum dilution restricted by the network [108]. This restriction causes gels of Type I polymers to undergo a continuous swollen-collapsed transition while Type II polymers separate into polymer rich and polymer dilute regions [78,108]. Higher degrees of cross-linking leads to a broadening of the transition as the network is further restricted (Fig. 3B) [96]. The enforced close confinement of polymer chains in this network amplifies composition dependent differences not apparent in the sharp CST of linear (co)polymer chains. For example, PNIPAM gels collapse over a significantly narrower temperature range than gels formed from homopolymer PMEO2MA or POEGMA-co-MEO2MA copolymers, Fig. 3C [97]. The same composition dependence on the breadth and magnitude of the temperature response is also evident, for example, when comparing the swelling of PNIPAM and PMEO2MA in the confines of polymer brushes (Fig. 3D) [64,67].
2.2.3. Polymer brushes on planar substrates
At a coarse level, the conformation of a neutral polymer brush is a balance of repulsive excluded volume interactions from overlapping chains that contribute to the swelling of the brush against the unfavourable loss of configurational entropy of swollen polymer chains [109]. The forced interaction of the grafted chains, as well as fluctuation of chain ends, leads to a broad continuous collapse of the brush with decreasing solvent quality (i.e. increasing temperature) instead of the first order transition of ungrafted polymers [110]. For example, a homopolymer POEGMA475 brush showed continuous conformational rearrangement from temperatures more than 50 °C below the CST of an equivalent ungrafted chain [111]. Note that a first-order transition is predicted for sufficiently high grafting density brushes in situations where there is a strong dependence of solvent quality on both concentration and temperature, as predicted for Type II polymers [35] and various theoretical models [108,112–115]. Here, vertical phase separation into a polymer rich region close to the substrate in equilibrium with a dilute tail is predicted at temperatures around the CST (Fig. 4A). Vertical phase separation has been observed directly in PNIPAM brushes by techniques sensitive to the average conformation perpendicular to the interface such as optical reflectometry (OR)
Fig. 2. Example coexistence curves for Type I (), II ( ) and III (––) polymers exhibiting an LCST. Horizontal lines are sample tie-lines for the Type III case.
T.J. Murdoch et al. / Journal of Colloid and Interface Science 526 (2018) 429–450 431


[116], spectroscopic ellipsometry (SE) [117], and neutron reflectometry (NR) (Fig. 4B) [14,66,118]. While all three techniques reveal a polymer dense region followed by a dilute tail, NR is significantly more sensitive to the volume fraction of polymer [66]. Consistent with theory, vertical phase separation was more apparent at higher grafting densities and/or MW [116,118,119]. In particular, Varma et al. [116] and Yim et al. [118] studied a large combination of MW and grafting densities of brushes and only observed vertical phase separation at the highest grafting density in each case (0.3 and 0.21 nm2 respectively). In contrast, volume fraction profiles of homopolymer PMEO2MA [67] (Fig. 4C) and copolymer P(MEO2MA-co-OEGMA300) [65] brushes, which have weaker intermolecular interactions, display a continuous transition between the swollen and collapsed states. An important prediction of numerical self-consistent field (nSCF) calculations is that the interfacial properties of the dilute region at the periphery of the brush remain essentially unchanged until T >> CST where a single dense, collapsed phase is formed [120,121]. Therefore comparing techniques that are sensitive to the overall swelling of the brush such as surface plasmon resonance [122], ellipsometry [64], and quartz crystal microbalance with dissipation monitoring (QCM-D) [64,121] with techniques primarily sensitive to the surface of the brush, such as contact angle (CA), can provide indirect evidence of vertical phase separation. Often, a jump in CA to greater values is observed in the vicinity of the LCST and is interpreted as an increase in the hydrophobicity of the brush surface [54,64,122–131]. However, careful captive bubble CA measurements indicate that this is likely due to out-of-equilibrium measurements with the perceived
increase in hydrophobicity resulting from decreased droplet penetration into the brush [111]. In general, studies show that the bulk properties of the brushes vary over a wide temperature range around the CST, while the surface properties vary over a narrow temperature range above the CST. Simultaneous QCM-D and ellipsometry measurements have also been used to indirectly probe the conformation of PNIPAM and POX brushes by utilising the greater sensitivity of QCM-D to dilute chains at the periphery of the brush [79]. Here, Type II PNIPAM brushes showed a larger difference than Type I POX brushes in the observed coupled mass from each technique at temperatures below the CST. These observations are consistent with a bottom-up collapse with increasing temperature. Normal force measurements using atomic force microscopy (AFM) [66,67,132,133] and the surface forces apparatus (SFA) [123] are important for predicting performance in applications such as controlled cell adhesion [134] and lubrication [135]. These measurements are typically performed at a sufficiently slow interaction velocity to achieve quasi-equilibrium conditions. In a good solvent at sufficiently high grafting densities purely repulsive interactions are observed which are well approximated by the seminal theories of neutral polymer brushes [65,123]. At lower grafting densities attractive bridging interactions are also observed between the brush and the probe [66,67,136]. These bridging interactions occur if the chain ends have sufficient conformational freedom [137], with the minimum grafting density found to be lower for strongly interacting polymers [136]. The magnitude of the attraction increases and the interaction range decreases above the CST due to stronger polymer-polymer interactions and the sharper polymer-solution interface [66,138]. Little hysteresis is
